  <Fragment slot="buying-guide">
    <BuyingGuideSection>
      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying guide: choosing a hand grinder for espresso under $100</h2>
      <p>
        Under $100, you’re always trading something off. The goal is picking the trade-off you can live with. Here’s
        how I’d decide if we were standing in your kitchen right now.
      </p>

      <h3>1) Pressurized vs non-pressurized: the fastest way to pick the right grinder</h3>
      <p>
        A <strong>pressurized basket</strong> is more forgiving. It creates resistance for you, so the grinder doesn’t
        have to be perfect. A <strong>non-pressurized basket</strong> is not forgiving. Your grinder has to create the
        right resistance by making a consistent espresso-fine grind.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you’re not sure which you have, a quick clue is the basket itself. Pressurized baskets usually have one
        tiny exit hole (or a “double wall” design). Non-pressurized baskets have lots of little holes. If you’re using
        non-pressurized and you want to avoid pain, pick the grinder with the best control in this list.
      </p>

      <h3>2) Buy adjustment control, not marketing</h3>
      <p>
        Espresso is sensitive. Small changes matter. If your grinder feels like it makes big jumps between settings,
        you’ll have a harder time finding the sweet spot. That’s why “more precise” grinders usually feel cheaper in
        the long run. You waste less coffee.
      </p>

      <h3>3) Think about effort and ergonomics (seriously)</h3>
      <p>
        The best hand grinder is the one you’ll actually use. If the handle feels awkward, or the grip feels slippery,
        you’ll get tired fast. If you mostly drink medium and dark roasts, grinding is usually manageable. If you love
        light roasts, expect more effort at espresso-fine settings.
      </p>

      <h3>4) Don’t ignore cleaning</h3>
      <p>
        Espresso creates fines (tiny powdery particles). Over time, they build up and can push flavors toward bitter
        and “muddy.” A quick brush-out weekly helps. Every few weeks, a deeper clean brings the grinder back to life.
        It’s one of the easiest upgrades you can do for flavor.
      </p>

      <h3>5) Build a simple routine so your grinder feels “better” than it is</h3>
      <p>
        This is my favorite trick for budget gear: make your process consistent. Same dose. Same yield. Same tamp.
        Change one thing at a time. Your grinder will feel more predictable, and your espresso will get better faster.
      </p>

      <h3>6) Don’t chase perfect numbers — chase a cup you actually like</h3>
      <p>
        Espresso advice on the internet can get weirdly strict, fast. Exact shot times. Exact ratios. Exact everything.
        Those rules can help you learn, but they can also make you feel like you’re failing.
      </p>
      <p>
        Here’s a friendlier way to use a budget hand grinder: use the numbers as a starting point, then let taste make
        the final call. If your shot tastes sour and thin, tighten the grind a little. If it tastes harsh and dry,
        loosen it a little. When it starts tasting sweeter and smoother, you’re getting closer. You don’t need perfect
        gear to get a great cup — you need small, repeatable steps.
      </p>

      <p>
        Want to zoom out and see what a true espresso grinder looks like above this budget? Start with
        <a href="/posts/best-burr-grinder-for-espresso.html">best burr grinder for espresso</a>.
      </p>
    </BuyingGuideSection>
